{"63": {"id": "63", "title": "Open source and accessibility: Empowering people with disabilities globally", "description": "Open source has become an integral part of the software that much of humanity uses to live, work, learn, and play. However, it's frequently unclear whether open source helps or hinders access for those with disabilities. 

Join this panel discussion to learn more about the current state of open source accessibility, and how individual developers and open source communities can help accelerate access for people with disabilities globally.", "speakers": ["Ed Summers", "Joe Devon", "Joshua Miele", "Christine Mendoza"], "tracks": ["Developer Experience"], "day": "Wednesday, Oct 30", "time": "12:00 p.m. Wednesday, Oct 30", "mode": "Recorded"}, "60": {"id": "60", "title": "Why (and how) IKEA, WirelessCar, and SAP adopted GitHub Advanced Security", "description": "Billions are spent globally to enhance application development security, and yet the results are underwhelming. Cyber incidents and hacks are more frequent than ever. Inside a company's walls, competing priorities between security and engineering teams can create friction. This leaves developers overwhelmed and security teams struggling to enforce the necessary actions, especially when AppSec tool reports return a sea of false positives.

In this GitHub-moderated panel, experts from IKEA, WirelessCar, and SAP will discuss how they address these challenges, reduce friction in AppSec, and utilize GitHub Advanced Security (GHAS) to stay at the forefront of innovation.", "speakers": ["Anja Loether", "Rajeev Kumar Jain", "Viktor Lindström", "Aline Senart"], "tracks": ["Developer Experience", "Security"], "day": "Wednesday, Oct 30", "time": "11:00 a.m. Wednesday, Oct 30", "mode": "Recorded"}, "19": {"id": "19", "title": "Bridging the gap: Building a strong connection between business and product development", "description": "Step into an immersive group collaboration experience at the Discussions Lounge, where we'll divide into two teams to determine whether business or product development should take the initiative, tackling the age-old debate: what comes first, the chicken or the egg? We'll role-play as business and product teams and work to find common ground. We'll also learn to identify when developers should take the first step to bridge the gap between business development and product development. Through dynamic discussions and interactive problem solving, we'll explore effective strategies for fostering cross-team collaboration, aligning priorities, maintaining clear communication, and driving successful outcomes.", "speakers": ["Chris Alex Bauer"], "tracks": ["Developer Experience"], "day": "Tuesday, Oct 29", "time": "12:00 p.m. Tuesday, Oct 29", "mode": "In-person"}}

{"34": {"id": "34", "title": "Tap into the power of AI, NTT DATA InnerSource, and GitHub to supercharge innovation and collaboration", "description": "In the vortex of today's digital revolution, AI is the game-changer that propels organizations into the future, merging the streams of innovation and collaboration into a powerful river of progress. The session, "Tap into the power of AI, NTT DATA InnerSource, and GitHub to supercharge innovation and collaboration," promises a deep dive into how AI is revolutionizing the way we think about enterprise collaboration and development. 

", "speakers": ["Manuel Sánchez", "Sergio Sisternes"], "tracks": ["AI", "Developer Experience"], "day": "Tuesday, Oct 29", "time": "2:00 p.m. Tuesday, Oct 29", "mode": "Recorded"}, "38": {"id": "38", "title": "Securing the future: Found means fixed with AI-driven application security", "description": "AI is far from reaching its peak in application security. Join Nick Liffen, director of GitHub Advanced Security, and Niroshan Rajadurai, VP, GTM, at GitHub, as they share how GitHub applies AI to help streamline remediation and enhance alert interpretability. This session will delve into real-world applications and a future where AI fortifies defenses and helps preemptively identify and mitigate emerging threats. This session is designed for developers, security experts, and executives alike. Come to learn and stay for the exciting conclusion. Our speakers have a special surprise planned!", "speakers": ["Nick Liffen", "Niroshan Rajadurai"], "tracks": ["AI", "Security"], "day": "Tuesday, Oct 29", "time": "3:00 p.m. Tuesday, Oct 29", "mode": "Recorded"}, "4": {"id": "4", "title": "Cha-ching! How to attract funding for your open source projects", "description": "There are many amazing stories about open source projects that have successfully attracted funding. Those dollars can translate to hiring more developers, speeding the release timeline, and tightening security. 

In this session, Anjuan Simmons, staff engineering manager at GitHub, will walk through real-life use cases, challenges faced and overcome, and outline key elements of successful funding profiles. Anjuan and members of GitHub's Open Source Funding team will also review attendee funding profiles live and provide real-time feedback and actionable changes that you can immediately make to help improve your profile and attract funding to your projects.", "speakers": ["Anjuan Simmons"], "tracks": ["Developer Experience"], "day": "Tuesday, Oct 29", "time": "10:00 a.m. Tuesday, Oct 29", "mode": "In-person"}}

{"62": {"id": "62", "title": "No training required: Easy ML model deployment using Arm-based GitHub Runners", "description": "In the dynamic landscape of machine learning operations (MLOps), streamlined workflows are essential for successful model deployment. This technical workshop facilitated by Arm's Jason Andrews, distinguished engineer, and Pareena Verma, principal solutions architect, focuses on leveraging Arm-based runners within GitHub Actions to create robust MLOps pipelines. This session is tailored for machine learning use cases and will explore how to deploy pre-trained and quantized Large Language Models (LLMs)—without the need for additional training.
", "speakers": ["Jason Andrews", "Pareena Verma"], "tracks": ["Developer Experience"], "day": "Wednesday, Oct 30", "time": "12:00 p.m. Wednesday, Oct 30", "mode": "In-person"}, "43": {"id": "43", "title": "Developer’s Cafe: Let's chat and co-create the future of development with AI", "description": "Some of the best conversations happen over coffee. That's why we're inviting you to the "Developer's Cafe," facilitated by Jenny Hwang, Julie Stuart, and Ya Gao, all from the user research team at GitHub. We all have a hand in co-creating the future of development with AI, and this space is designed for intimate conversations with fellow attendees to discuss how we can influence our best-case scenarios for using AI in software development.", "speakers": ["Jenny Hwang", "Julie Stuart", "Ya Gao"], "tracks": ["AI", "Developer Experience"], "day": "Tuesday, Oct 29", "time": "4:00 p.m. Tuesday, Oct 29", "mode": "In-person"}, "59": {"id": "59", "title": "Optimizing your dev flow with GitHub Copilot", "description": "New tools always come with a learning curve, and GitHub Copilot is no exception. Just like working with a new colleague, collaborating with AI takes practice, experimentation, and collaboration.

GitHub Developer Advocates Kedasha Kerr and Christopher Harrison will share their insights on how to get the most out of GitHub Copilot. They’ll walk through real-world examples highlighting the many ways you’ll interact with your AI-pair programmer. You’ll leave with several useful tips you can apply to your flow, helping you get guidance on tasks of all sizes.", "speakers": ["Christopher Harrison", "Kedasha Kerr"], "tracks": ["AI"], "day": "Wednesday, Oct 30", "time": "11:00 a.m. Wednesday, Oct 30", "mode": "In-person"}}

{"72": {"id": "72", "title": "Simplifying collaboration across multiple organizations using GitHub Projects", "description": "GitHub Issues and GitHub Projects support engineers writing code and leaders collaborating at a large scale across organizations. Join Claire Stehley, staff technical program manager at GitHub, and Gabriel Marangoni Moita, product owner of GitHub at SAP, as they unpack the benefits of collaborative project management with clear and transparent communication. They'll walk through a GitHub and SAP partnership case study, showcasing how GitHub's native tooling fosters collaboration, enabling teams to work together as one. You'll learn more about the challenges faced, how they were resolved, and the successful engineering execution model GitHub uses to drive our partnerships.

", "speakers": ["Claire Stehley", "Gabriel Marangoni Moita"], "tracks": ["Developer Experience"], "day": "Wednesday, Oct 30", "time": "2:00 p.m. Wednesday, Oct 30", "mode": "In-person"}, "75": {"id": "75", "title": "From data scientist to developer: How GlaxoSmithKline upskilled 1,300 GitHub beginners in one year", "description": "GlaxoSmithKline (GSK) set a groundbreaking precedent within the pharmaceutical industry by leveraging GitHub for clinical trial reporting. In this session, Eleanor Sparling, data scientist at GSK, will discuss how GSK tackled large-scale change and upskilling, and redefined workflows to capitalize on automation. Eleanor will also share the downstream effects on quality control and measures taken to ensure regulatory compliance.", "speakers": ["Eleanor Sparling"], "tracks": ["Developer Experience"], "day": "Wednesday, Oct 30", "time": "2:00 p.m. Wednesday, Oct 30", "mode": "Recorded"}, "4": {"id": "4", "title": "Cha-ching! How to attract funding for your open source projects", "description": "There are many amazing stories about open source projects that have successfully attracted funding. Those dollars can translate to hiring more developers, speeding the release timeline, and tightening security. 

In this session, Anjuan Simmons, staff engineering manager at GitHub, will walk through real-life use cases, challenges faced and overcome, and outline key elements of successful funding profiles. Anjuan and members of GitHub's Open Source Funding team will also review attendee funding profiles live and provide real-time feedback and actionable changes that you can immediately make to help improve your profile and attract funding to your projects.", "speakers": ["Anjuan Simmons"], "tracks": ["Developer Experience"], "day": "Tuesday, Oct 29", "time": "10:00 a.m. Tuesday, Oct 29", "mode": "In-person"}}

{"53": {"id": "53", "title": "Open source for all: Skilling the next generation of developers", "description": "There are similarities between diversity and inclusion efforts in tech today and software development in the early days of open source. That is to say: even with many resources and funds invested, efforts are often disjointed, siloed, or sidelined. As GitHub scales to becomes home for one billion global developers, we aim to fix this.

Join facilitators, Ruth Ikegah, open source consultant at CHAOSS, and Sarah Oyetubo, senior DI&B program manager at GitHub, for a discussion on how to foster collaboration and help skill new developers, lowering the barrier of entry to open source for all.", "speakers": ["Sarah Oyetubo", "Ruth Ikegah"], "tracks": ["AI", "Developer Experience"], "day": "Wednesday, Oct 30", "time": "10:00 a.m. Wednesday, Oct 30", "mode": "In-person"}, "68": {"id": "68", "title": "Shaping an inclusive AI future by empowering women in data", "description": "Diverse voices are indispensable in steering the course of data—and its profound impact on AI. In this session, Autumn Nash, software development engineer at AWS and Merry Cimakasky, cloud access engineer at Splunk, will facilitate a conversation about the reciprocal benefits that come from investing in and enhancing women's data skills specifically.

They will share unique challenges faced by women in tech, which includes military spouses, women of color, and mothers, and will help attendees recognize and emphasize how imperative it is to build and foster a diverse workforce in data to combat bias. Learn how to attract and retain women in data-centric fields, and help to shape more fair and accurate AI.", "speakers": ["Autumn Nash", "Merry Cimakasky"], "tracks": ["AI"], "day": "Wednesday, Oct 30", "time": "1:00 p.m. Wednesday, Oct 30", "mode": "In-person"}, "17": {"id": "17", "title": "Unlocking creativity within the constraints of corporate development", "description": "Enterprises are tightly regulated and necessary controls limit what employees can do, often to the detriment of developers. A developer's ability to innovate and experiment is stymied by privileged admin access to corporate-issued devices and developer tools that are pre-configured and deployed by central IT. Join this discussion facilitated by Jim Richer, distinguished engineer, at TD Bank, to take a look at what these controls are and how to enforce them—all while still championing creativity.  ", "speakers": ["Jim Richer"], "tracks": ["Developer Experience"], "day": "Tuesday, Oct 29", "time": "11:00 a.m. Tuesday, Oct 29", "mode": "In-person"}}

{"19": {"id": "19", "title": "Bridging the gap: Building a strong connection between business and product development", "description": "Step into an immersive group collaboration experience at the Discussions Lounge, where we'll divide into two teams to determine whether business or product development should take the initiative, tackling the age-old debate: what comes first, the chicken or the egg? We'll role-play as business and product teams and work to find common ground. We'll also learn to identify when developers should take the first step to bridge the gap between business development and product development. Through dynamic discussions and interactive problem solving, we'll explore effective strategies for fostering cross-team collaboration, aligning priorities, maintaining clear communication, and driving successful outcomes.", "speakers": ["Chris Alex Bauer"], "tracks": ["Developer Experience"], "day": "Tuesday, Oct 29", "time": "12:00 p.m. Tuesday, Oct 29", "mode": "In-person"}, "30": {"id": "30", "title": "Collaborative API creation, testing, and deployment with Postman", "description": "Software development moves fast, making collaboration a vital part of building robust and innovative solutions. This session delves into the strategies and features that make Postman, a leading API development platform, a catalyst for effective teamwork and developer productivity.

Join Alex Barnett, head of DevRel & Community at Postman, to learn how Postman's collaboration-centric approach transforms the developer experience and makes it easier for teams to build, test, and deploy high-quality APIs.", "speakers": ["Alex Barnett"], "tracks": ["Developer Experience"], "day": "Tuesday, Oct 29", "time": "2:00 p.m. Tuesday, Oct 29", "mode": "In-person"}, "9": {"id": "9", "title": "Figma for developers: Designed to ship great products, faster", "description": "Effective collaboration between developers and designers is critical for product development—and the right tools can help. Developers can ship quality code faster when they don't have to switch contexts to stay in sync with designers. Clear communication and the shared language of design systems allow teams to streamline the hand-off process and build more efficiently at scale. 

Join Jake Albaugh, developer advocate at Figma, to discover new features that help developers optimize how they work across Figma's Dev Mode and their codebases, and bring design and development closer together.", "speakers": ["Jake Albaugh"], "tracks": ["Developer Experience"], "day": "Tuesday, Oct 29", "time": "11:00 a.m. Tuesday, Oct 29", "mode": "In-person"}}

{"27": {"id": "27", "title": "Getting seamless mobile development from code to app store like a pro", "description": "Create a seamless journey through mobile app development, from initial coding to your app store release. Learn how to address common challenges and streamline processes with GitHub Actions workflows, tailored to your needs. In this session, Jenn Robison, a principal software engineer, will showcase tools like Expo Application Services (EAS) for testing, debugging, and deployment, and Doppler for secrets management.


", "speakers": ["Jenn Robison"], "tracks": ["Developer Experience"], "day": "Tuesday, Oct 29", "time": "1:00 p.m. Tuesday, Oct 29", "mode": "Recorded"}, "17": {"id": "17", "title": "Unlocking creativity within the constraints of corporate development", "description": "Enterprises are tightly regulated and necessary controls limit what employees can do, often to the detriment of developers. A developer's ability to innovate and experiment is stymied by privileged admin access to corporate-issued devices and developer tools that are pre-configured and deployed by central IT. Join this discussion facilitated by Jim Richer, distinguished engineer, at TD Bank, to take a look at what these controls are and how to enforce them—all while still championing creativity.  ", "speakers": ["Jim Richer"], "tracks": ["Developer Experience"], "day": "Tuesday, Oct 29", "time": "11:00 a.m. Tuesday, Oct 29", "mode": "In-person"}, "52": {"id": "52", "title": "Let's build an app with GitHub Copilot in 40 minutes!", "description": "Use GitHub Copilot as your AI pair programmer to develop a real app with little time and information. In this session, Bryant Jimin Son and Ari LiVigni, both senior cloud solutions engineers from the GitHub Expert Delivery team, will walk through a real-world use case: building a fitness app from end to end. Together, you'll create a full stack of technologies for the infrastructure, frontend, and backend using the latest Copilot features.
", "speakers": ["Ari LiVigni", "Bryant Jimin Son"], "tracks": ["AI"], "day": "Wednesday, Oct 30", "time": "10:00 a.m. Wednesday, Oct 30", "mode": "In-person"}}

{"85": {"id": "85", "title": "The latest and greatest ways to manage repositories at scale", "description": "Are you striving for consistent and efficient management across your GitHub organization’s repositories? Discover how our new enhancements can ease your approach. In this session, you’ll learn how to achieve naming consistency, manage repository visibility, and streamline administration across all or specific groups of repositories. With features that support both automation enthusiasts and those preferring a manual approach, we have a few new things to show you to help better manage your repositories at scale.", "speakers": ["Patrick Knight", "Aaron Scofield"], "tracks": ["Developer Experience"], "day": "Wednesday, Oct 30", "time": "3:00 p.m. Wednesday, Oct 30", "mode": "In-person"}, "10": {"id": "10", "title": "Using your repository for RAG: Learnings from GitHub Copilot Chat", "description": "Retrieval Augmented Generation (RAG) is a tool that can enrich questions sent to AI models with relevant data from specific knowledge bases, to help models tailor their answers to that domain. But how do engineers know what's "relevant"? Or, if the knowledge base is your repo, can the model respond with a solution that follows your coding practices?

In this session, Kim-Adeline Miguel, senior software engineer at GitHub, will approach RAG from an engineering perspective and walk through some lessons learned while building a RAG workflow using GitHub Copilot Chat.", "speakers": ["Kim-Adeline Miguel"], "tracks": ["AI"], "day": "Tuesday, Oct 29", "time": "11:00 a.m. Tuesday, Oct 29", "mode": "Recorded"}, "46": {"id": "46", "title": "The evidence is in: Take a new approach to software asset inventory ", "description": "Software asset inventory is an often overlooked, but critical component of automating policy enforcement in the DevOps pipeline. Poor inventory paired with broad policies can subject developers to having unnecessary or inaccurate requirements added to their workflows.

In this session, Michael Edenzon, CEO and co-founder of Fianu, will outline the common gaps in existing software inventories and provide simple, actionable steps that DevOps engineers can take to establish an evidence-based software asset inventory. You'll learn how the powerful combo of Fianu and GitHub can unblock even the most entrenched manual processes.", "speakers": ["Michael Edenzon"], "tracks": ["Developer Experience", "Security"], "day": "Tuesday, Oct 29", "time": "4:00 p.m. Tuesday, Oct 29", "mode": "Recorded"}}

{"24": {"id": "24", "title": "GitHub Copilot: Leading the AI revolution in software development", "description": "Developers and enterprises adopting AI coding assistants expect these tools to be increasingly accurate and personalized to their needs. GitHub Copilot is leading the charge, delivering major improvements in code suggestion quality, enhanced customization via fine-tuned models, and building a growing ecosystem with extensions. Join our partner Adobe and GitHub's Shuyin Zhao, VP of product management, and Simina Pasat, senior director of product management, to see all the latest Copilot innovations. You'll also learn how collaboration in GitHub.com is getting better with the power of AI agents and how you can use new, optimized workflows in the age of AI.", "speakers": ["Shuyin Zhao", "Simina Pasat"], "tracks": ["AI"], "day": "Tuesday, Oct 29", "time": "12:00 p.m. Tuesday, Oct 29", "mode": "Livestream"}, "83": {"id": "83", "title": "In case you missed it: Powerful AI agents and AI-native workflows across GitHub", "description": "GitHub Copilot has a simple goal: to increase developer productivity and accelerate the pace of software development. 

Copilot started its journey in the IDE, but GitHub's research reveals that the average developer only spends about two hours a day coding. That's why GitHub is evolving to bring more Copilot experiences front and center, with powerful AI agents and customizations for your organizational knowledge. 

In this fast-paced demo, Tim Rogers, senior product manager at GitHub, will show how GitHub is infusing AI across the platform in new and magical ways to boost developer productivity and bring small moments of delight to their day. ", "speakers": ["Tim Rogers"], "tracks": ["AI"], "day": "Wednesday, Oct 30", "time": "3:00 p.m. Wednesday, Oct 30", "mode": "Recorded"}, "85": {"id": "85", "title": "The latest and greatest ways to manage repositories at scale", "description": "Are you striving for consistent and efficient management across your GitHub organization’s repositories? Discover how our new enhancements can ease your approach. In this session, you’ll learn how to achieve naming consistency, manage repository visibility, and streamline administration across all or specific groups of repositories. With features that support both automation enthusiasts and those preferring a manual approach, we have a few new things to show you to help better manage your repositories at scale.", "speakers": ["Patrick Knight", "Aaron Scofield"], "tracks": ["Developer Experience"], "day": "Wednesday, Oct 30", "time": "3:00 p.m. Wednesday, Oct 30", "mode": "In-person"}}
